; preludes: form-stdlib/core.fk
;
; witness-theorem-band — the core theorem under three-way proof itself
; (docs/coherence-substrate/witness-theorem.form). Urs: "the reason for it to
; be observable is to show FAILING cases — not all failing, not all passing,
; some also SILENT — and we need shared trust, three-way proven: we trust two
; of our brothers and sisters over any stranger."
;
; A real witness speaks axiom-1's FULL vocabulary — 1 (pass), 0 (fail), nothing
; (silence). A check that can only pass is a mirror, not a witness (AUTHORING.md:
; "a band that only checks 1==1 is theatre"). The honest witness ABSTAINS at the
; boundary it cannot judge — silence is a first-class answer, not a forced verdict.
;
; And the TRUST is not in any one voice: it is the CONCERT. This band's own
; three-way agreement (validate.sh: 1 ok, 0 divergent) IS the shared trust — two
; siblings confirming the third. We trust the spread three kernels agree on —
; including where it FAILS and where it falls SILENT — over any stranger's word.
;
; `judge` is the witness: x>=1 -> pass(1), x<=-1 -> fail(0), x==0 -> silence(nothing).
; The boundary (0) is the case it honestly cannot decide, so it abstains.
;
; Verdict 31 when the full witness vocabulary holds, three-way:
;   1   PASS is witnessed — a clear positive yields 1
;   2   FAIL is witnessed AS DATA — a clear negative yields 0 (an observable
;       fail, never an error or a crash; the witness shows failure plainly)
;   4   SILENCE is witnessed — the boundary it cannot judge yields nothing
;       (the empty, zero extent): abstention, not a forced false pass
;   8   THE SPREAD IS REAL — pass, fail, and silence are mutually distinct;
;       the witness does not collapse them (not-all-passing, not-all-failing)
;   16  THE GROUND OF TRUST — the same witness over the same inputs yields the
;       same spread (determinism); shared trust is possible only because the
;       three siblings CAN agree, and this band agreeing three-way IS that trust
(do
    (defn judge (x)
        (if (le 1 x) 1
            (if (le x (sub 0 1)) 0
                (empty))))

    (let c0 (if (eq (judge 5) 1) 1 0))

    (let c1 (if (eq (judge (sub 0 5)) 0) 2 0))

    ; SILENCE: the boundary yields the absence (len 0). Distinctness from
    ; pass/fail is by VALUE (c3), since the absence is the witness's THIRD reply,
    ; not a smaller integer — the spread is what makes the silence meaningful.
    (let c2 (if (eq (len (judge 0)) 0) 4 0))

    ; the spread: pass != fail, and the silent answer is the absence while the
    ; pass answer is a present integer 1 — three genuinely different replies.
    (let c3 (if (eq (eq (judge 5) (judge (sub 0 5))) 0)
                (if (eq (judge 5) 1)
                    (if (eq (judge (sub 0 5)) 0) 8 0) 0) 0))

    (let c4 (if (eq (judge 5) (judge 5))
                (if (eq (judge (sub 0 5)) (judge (sub 0 5)))
                    (if (eq (len (judge 0)) (len (judge 0))) 16 0) 0) 0))

    (add c0 (add c1 (add c2 (add c3 c4)))))
